arXiv.abstract:
A new scheme for the short baseline electron antineutrino (${ ar{
u}}_{e}$) disappearance study is investigated. We propose to use an intense neutron emitter, $^{252}$Cf, which produces $^{8}$Li isotope through the $^{7}$Li(n,$\gamma$)$^{8}$Li reaction; $^{8}$Li is a ${ ar{
u}}_{e}$ emitter via $ eta^{-}$ decay. Because this ${ ar{
u}}_{e}$ source needs neither accelerator nor reactor facilities, the ${ ar{
u}}_{e}$ can be placed on any neutrino detectors as closely as possible. This short baseline circumstance with a suitable detector enables us to study the existence of possible sterile neutrinos, in particular, on 1 eV mass scale. Also, complementary comparison studies among different neutrino detectors can become feasible by using ${ ar{
u}}_{e}$ from the $^{8}$Li source. As an example, applications to hemisphere and cylinder shape scintillator detectors are performed in detail with the expectation signal modification by the sterile neutrino. Sensitivities to mass and mixing angles of sterile neutrinos are also presented for comparison with those of other neutrino experiments.

